POLIOMYELITIS - UPDATE (11): BRAZIL ex EQUATORIAL GUINEA, ENVIRONMENTAL SAMPLES, GLOBAL
***************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Brazil, WPV1, environmental samples, PAHO
[2] Global - Polio eradication inititative

******
[1] Brazil, WPV1, environmental samples, PAHO
Date: 21 Jun 2014
Source: PAHO [edited]
http://www.paho.org/hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=25922+&Itemid=999999&lang=pt


Upon detection of wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) in environmental samples from Brazil, the Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) / World Health Organization (WHO) recommends that Member States of the Region of the Americas continue to strengthen surveillance for cases of acute flaccid paralysis in order to rapidly detect any new instances of imported poliovirus and maintain high immunization coverage against polio.

On [18 Jun 2014], the Brazil International Health Regulations (IHR) National Focal Point (NFP) reported the detection of wild poliovirus type 1 (WPV1) in sewage samples collected in March 2014 at the International Airport of Viracopos located in Campinas, Sao Paulo. The WPV1 was detected in sewage only. The isolate was detected through routine environmental surveillance in Brazil that includes regular testing of sewage water from multiple sites. Brazil has been carrying out this routine surveillance for over 20 years. To date, there has been no reported suspected or confirmed case of paralytic polio in the country.

Genetic analysis of the WPV1 indicated a close match with a strain of polio recently isolated from a case of polio in Equatorial Guinea. The epidemiological investigation is ongoing.

Following detection of this isolate, the public health authorities in Brazil are strengthening surveillance of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP), engaging in an active search for AFP cases across the state of Sao Paulo. Brazil has conducted 2 national immunization campaigns per year, with oral polio vaccine from the 1980s until 2011. In 2012 and 2013, single vaccination campaigns were carried out. These campaigns have achieved vaccination coverage levels of over 95 percent in the last 8 years. Routine vaccination coverage has been above 95 percent in the municipality of Campinas as well as the State of Sao Paulo.

PAHO/WHO assesses the risk of further international spread of this virus from Brazil as very low given that there is a high level of immunity in the population as evidenced by the high levels of routine immunization coverage and periodic vaccination campaigns in the area, no evidence of WPV1 transmission thus far, and the response actions being implemented.

The Americas Region has been free of wild poliovirus transmission since 1991, and the last case of polio in Brazil occurred in 1989.

PAHO / WHO reminds Member States of the need to achieve and maintain high quality surveillance for timely detection and response to imported wild poliovirus. Member States are also reminded to achieve and maintain high vaccination coverage against polio in all municipalities. In this regard, Member States should analyze their coverage data systematically to be able to identify any areas with low vaccination coverage and intensify surveillance and vaccination in those areas accordingly.

PAHO / WHO reiterates that the recommendations made by the Technical Advisory Group meeting in Quito, Ecuador, held from [3 to 5 Jul 2013], remain valid; they include:
- All countries must reinforce activities aimed to achieve or maintain vaccination coverage greater than 95 percent in every district or municipality. If countries do not achieve that coverage, they must evaluate the accumulation of non-immunized people and conduct vaccination campaigns.
- All countries must continue to maintain adequate AFP surveillance in order for timely detection of imported, or the emergence of vaccine-derived, polioviruses (VDPVs), and must report such to PAHO / WHO in a timely manner to allow proper monitoring of the regional situation.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-PORT moderator RNA, based in Sao Paolo, Brazil, had the following comments [trans. from Port. and edited]:
"The detection of wild poliovirus type 1 in environmental samples, reported here, leads to some thoughts:

- The potential poliovirus circulation (and many others, such as, more recently, chikungunya) due to the intense and fluid movement of people between countries and continents with distinct epidemiologic realities; the International airport at Viracopos -- although not (yet) a transit point and entry point of passengers coming from international flights -- is a major, if not the main, cargo airport in Brazil, with aircraft coming from different countries from all continents. Coming with the cargo include the crews and other workers who work in the transport of products and goods between countries.

- Environmental monitoring, while not permitting an identification of the specific flight/plane where the identified poliovirus came from, namely from which aircraft and which individual, it does demonstrate the importance of this strategy as a potentially useful element for surveillance of poliovirus circulation, especially with the ongoing scenario of the WHO global alert (See Polio - World alert, WHO, Archive Number: 20140505.2452107 http://www.promedmail.org/direct.php?id=2452107), even in countries which have received certification of poliomyelitis eradication and have demonstrated adequate vaccination coverages and a well structured surveillance system for polio detection. The environmental monitoring, surely, must be understood as a strategy, a tool with the potential to qualify and guide further health surveillance, including monitoring vaccination coverage."

- As pointed out in the PAHO / WHO document, the identification of the virus only in a single environmental sample and having checked the origin of the virus (the virus is genetically related to a strain recently circulating in Equatorial Guinea), showing it was imported, the detection of the virus in environmental samples alone does not alter the status of Brazil with respect to poliomyelitis (certification of eradication) and does lead to emergency actions and specific recommendations. In contrast, the detection of the virus through environmental monitoring should be praised for being conducted, even though the country has been certified as having eradicated polio since 1994, as a means of keeping the polio eradication status and high vaccine coverages (obtained by routine immunization and the numerous National Vaccination Campaigns Against Polio).

- Above all, the present event reinforces both the maintenance of already existing and ongoing surveillance of acute flaccid paralysis and vaccination strategies (routine and in national campaigns) and points to the importance of discussion and potential adoption of specific strategies of vaccination for Brazilian travelers who go to countries where there is circulating poliovirus as well as those individuals coming to Brazil from foreign countries as tourists, migrants or refugees. - Mod.RNA"

Historically, the "birth" of the polio eradication initiative was in Brazil in the late 1970s and early 1980s when the MOH adopted the strategy of national vaccination campaigns as part of its polio control efforts (very much encouraged and assisted by Dr. Ciro de Quadros of PAHO; see Obituary: Ciro de Quadros 20140618.2515703). This moderator was fortunate to have worked with the Brazilian MOH as a consultant during that period and observed firsthand the dedication and determination of the MOH to addressing a serious problem with polio in the country. In 1980, there were 1342 confirmed cases of polio in Brazil; by 1989, there were 25, and by 1990 there were 0 (see http://apps.who.int/immunization_monitoring/globalsummary/timeseries/tsincidencepolio.html for the global polio trends). Brazil demonstrated that the use of the national vaccination campaigns could markedly reduce circulation of the WPV, and the use of local campaigns for "mop up" activities could eliminate inadequately vaccinated pockets leading to interruption of WPV circulation in a country.

The identification of the WPV1 in the sewage sample served as a reminder of the importance to maintain the high levels of vaccination coverages so that the herd immunity created by the high vaccination coverages would prevent local circulation of the WPV1, and prevent actual cases of paralytic polio in the country. In 2014 to date, there have been 4 confirmed cases of WPV1 in Equatorial Guinea, with the date of onset of the most recent case 3 Apr 2014, after the date of isolation of the WPV in the Brazilian environmental sampling (see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek.aspx and section [2] below).

Equatorial Guinea was formerly known as the Spanish Guinea, on the west coast of Africa. Official languages of the country include Spanish, French and Portuguese. For a map showing its location in Africa and the world view, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equatorial_Guinea. For the HealthMap/ProMED map of Equatorial Guinea, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2558067,60. For a map showing the location of the Viracopos airport in Campinhas, Brazil, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viracopos_International_Airport. For the HealthMap/ProMED map of Brazil, see < https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2558067,6> - Mod.MPP]

